The paper focuses on developing a technique for analyzing and evolving highly configurable software systems, which falls under the software engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The technique proposed, iGen, involves dynamic analysis and inference of interactions, which could also be classified under programming languages (cs.PL) and systems and control (cs.SY) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the use of machine learning algorithms to process the coverage data, which could be related to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of iGen in automated testing and verification, which could be related to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category.
